## Overview

The Sakhalin Ainu verb stem can host a stacked sequence of affixes that change how many
arguments the verb takes and how those arguments map onto the clause. Following <Cite key="Chiri 1942" paren={false} />, the verb's subcategorisation divides predicatives
into <strong>complete</strong> verbs (完用詞), which need no object and mark a first-person-singular
subject with a suffix, and <strong>incomplete</strong> verbs (不完用詞), which require a complement or
object and mark it with a prefix. Valency-changing morphology is precisely what shifts a
stem between these classes: an applicative or causative turns a complete verb into an
incomplete one, while a reflexive, reciprocal, or antipassive turns an incomplete verb
back into a complete one (<Cite key="Chiri 1942" page="§33" paren={false} />).

Two broad sets are attested. <strong>Valency-increasing</strong> devices are suffixal — the causatives
and transitivisers <W w="-ka" gloss="CAUS" />, <W w="-re" gloss="CAUS" />, the
Sakhalin-specific <W w="-te" gloss="CAUS" />, the bare vowel suffix, and the
plural-causee <W w="-yara" gloss="CAUS" /> — together with the prefixal <strong>applicatives</strong> <W w="e-" gloss="APPL" />, <W w="o-" gloss="APPL" />, and <W w="ko-" gloss="APPL" />. <strong>Valency-decreasing</strong> devices are prefixal: the reciprocal <W w="u-" gloss="RECP" />,
the reflexives <W w="yay-" gloss="REFL" /> and <W w="si-" gloss="REFL" />, the antipassive <W w="i-" gloss="ANTIP" />, and the anticausative suffix <W w="-ke" gloss="ANTIC" />. The
last is treated by <Cite key="Bugaeva 2025" paren={false} /> as standing in equipollent
opposition to the direct causative. These operations may stack, making the language
polysynthetic and incorporating (<Cite key="Chiri 1942" page="§24-25" />; <Cite key="Bugaeva 2014" />).

## Causatives and transitivisers

<Cite key="Chiri 1942" paren={false} /> (§55) catalogues five suffixal devices, all of
which can derive either a plain transitive or a causative — Chiri's combined "transitive
or causative voice" (他動相又は使役相). The most basic is a bare <strong>vowel suffix</strong> on CVC
roots, which <Cite key="Bugaeva 2025" paren={false} /> analyses as the direct causative
in opposition to the anticausative: <W w="mak-a" gloss="open" /> 'open (tr.)', <W w="per-e" gloss="break" /> 'break (tr.)'. The suffix <Gl t="CAUS" /> <W w="-ka" />
causativises complete (stative) verbs, as in <W w="hure" gloss="be red" /> → <W w="hureka" gloss="redden" />:

<Example
	ain="hure-ka"
	gloss="be.red-CAUS"
	free="‘make red, redden’"
	cite="Chiri 1942" page="§55(3)"
	dialect="Sakhalin" />

The same <W w="-ka" /> is what transitivises the intransitive <W w="tuhse" gloss="jump" />
'jump' into 'kick', the base form against which the applicative is contrasted below:

<Example
	ain="suma kema ani tuhse-ka"
	surface="Suma kema ani tuhseka."
	gloss="rock foot 3SG.O/with 3SG.A/3SG.O/jump-CAUS"
	free="‘(S)he kicked the rock with [his/her] foot.’"
	cite="Murasaki 1979" page="32"
	dialect="West"
	note="Non-applicative base: the instrument ‘foot’ is an oblique introduced by ani." />

The general causative is <W w="-re" gloss="CAUS" /> ~ <W w="-te" gloss="CAUS" />, and its
allomorphy is one of the clearest Sakhalin-defining points of valency morphology. After
vowel-final stems the form is <Gl t="CAUS" /> <W w="-re" /> (<W w="e" gloss="eat" /> → <W w="ere" gloss="feed" />, <W w="ku" gloss="drink" /> → <W w="kure" gloss="give to drink" />).
After consonant-final stems the form is <Gl t="CAUS" /> <W w="-te" />, and critically, after
an <W w="-r" />-final stem Sakhalin uses <W w="-te" /> with the stem-final <strong>r &gt; n</strong>
(<Cite key="Chiri 1942" page="§15, §55(4)" paren={false} />). This contrasts directly with Hokkaido,
which uses <W w="-e" /> here (Hokk. *kore*, *nukare*):

<Example
	ain="kor-te"
	gloss="have-CAUS"
	free="‘cause to have’ = ‘give’ (→ konte)"
	cite="Chiri 1942" page="§15(ロ), §55(4)(ロ)"
	dialect="Sakhalin"
	note="Causative -te triggers stem-final r > n, yielding konte; cf. Hokkaido kore." />

The parallel form <W w="nukar-te" gloss="show" /> → *nukante* 'show' (Hokk. *nukare*) works
the same way. This <W w="konte" gloss="give" /> 'give' is exactly what surfaces in
West-coast texts, confirming the rule outside the descriptive literature:

<Example
	ain="tama in=kor-te"
	surface="Tamà in=konte."
	gloss="jewel 1SG.O=3SG.A/have-CAUS"
	free="‘You gave me the jewel.’"
	cite="Chiba (archive)"
	dialect="West"
	note="kon-te from kor-te; West-central; segmentation mine." />

A further pair of causatives keys to verbal number: <W w="-ke" /> for a singular object, <W w="-te" /> for a plural one, on the n~p alternating deictic-motion verb <W w="ahun" gloss="enter" /> / <W w="ahup" gloss="enter (pl.)" /> 'enter':

<Example
	ain="ahun-ke ; ahup-te"
	gloss="enter.SG-CAUS ; enter.PL-CAUS"
	free="‘put one in’ / ‘put many in’"
	cite="Chiri 1942" page="§35, §55(2)"
	dialect="Sakhalin"
	note="Singular- vs plural-object causatives on ahun/ahup." />

Finally, <Cite key="Chiri 1942" page="§55(5)" /> notes a pluralic causative <W w="-yara" gloss="CAUS" /> (~ <W w="-ara" />, with the glide dropping after a consonant)
marking a <strong>plural causee</strong>, illustrated by <W w="e-yara" /> 'make (people) eat'. The same
suffix combines productively with the reflexive <W w="si-" />: Chiri's <W w="si-nomi-yara" gloss="REFL-worship-CAUS" /> 'have oneself worshipped' (alongside <W w="si-kasuy-re" /> 'have oneself helped') shows <W w="-yara" /> selected, rather than <W w="-re" />, precisely where the causee is construed as a plurality of worshippers
(<Cite key="Chiri 1942" page="§53(2)(ニ)" paren={false} />). We therefore analyse <W w="-yara" /> not as
a free alternant of the general causative but as its <strong>number-sensitive</strong> counterpart: it
spells out the same Slot-IV causative head as <W w="-re" /> ~ <W w="-te" />, adding a
[+plural] specification on the causee argument (cf. the singular-vs-plural-object split <W w="-ke" />/<W w="-te" /> on <W w="ahun" />/<W w="ahup" /> above). On the cognate
Hokkaido marker <W w="-yar" />, <Cite key="Bugaeva 2025" paren={false} /> shows the suffix
is an <strong>indefinite causative</strong> that does not change valency; the two analyses are
compatible if the Sakhalin reflex retains the plural-causee value Chiri records while the
indefinite-agent reading is the Hokkaido innovation. A dedicated West-versus-East frequency
count is not yet possible — the form is rare in the romanised West-coast texts — but the
suffix is securely Sakhalin-wide, being catalogued by Chiri (whose data span both coasts)
and surviving in the pan-Ainu <W w="-yar" />.

## Applicatives e-, o-, ko-

The prefixes <W w="e-" gloss="APPL" />, <W w="o-" gloss="APPL" />, and <W w="ko-" gloss="APPL" /> are labelled the "applicative voice" (指相/充当相) by Chiri and
Kindaichi (<Cite key="Chiri 1942" page="§56-58" paren={false} />). They license, as a core argument, a
participant that the colloquial language otherwise expresses with a postposition.
Functionally they <strong>transitivise</strong> intransitives and <strong>ditransitivise</strong> transitives
(<Cite key="Bugaeva 2006" paren={false} />, for Hokkaido — the clearest typological
statement; the same prefixes operate in Sakhalin). The semantic range is broad: <W w="e-" /> covers instrument, location, allative, content, purpose, cause, and
comitative; <W w="o-" /> covers place, goal, and source; <W w="ko-" /> covers goal,
addressee, and comitative.

<Cite key="Dal Corso 2025" paren={false} /> (§4.4.1) confirms the applicative analysis for
Sakhalin with a minimal pair built on the 'kick' verb above. Where the non-applicative base
leaves the instrument 'foot' as an oblique, the applicative <W w="e-" /> promotes it to an
indirect object:

<Example
	ain="suma kema e-tuhse-ka"
	surface="Suma kema e-tuhseka."
	gloss="rock foot APPL-3SG.A/3SG.O/3SG.IO/jump-CAUS"
	free="‘(S)he kicked the rock with [his/her] foot.’"
	cite="Murasaki 1979" page="32"
	dialect="West"
	note="Applicative e- promotes the instrument ‘foot’ to indirect object; cf. the base above." />

Two cautions attach to the Sakhalin data. First, not every prefixal <W w="e-" /> is an
applicative: <Cite key="Dal Corso 2025" paren={false} /> argues that some tokens are better
read as the deictic element <W w="he-" gloss="head" /> marking goal-directed motion, which
phonologically reduces to <W w="e-" />:

<Example
	ain="cise or-ta (h)e-sirepa-an"
	surface="Cise oxta e-sirepa-an."
	gloss="house place-LOC DEI.head-arrive-INDEF.S"
	free="‘I arrived up to the house.’"
	cite="Piłsudski 1912" page="160"
	dialect="East"
	note="Analysed not as applicative but as a reduced deictic he- ‘head’." />

Second, Sakhalin <W w="e-" /> and <W w="ko-" /> also have valency-<strong>preserving</strong> secondary
functions that are common on the East coast but scant in the West (see Dialectal variation).
The aspectual/presentative <W w="e-a" /> 'be standing/sitting (right there)' is one such use:

<Example
	ain="ta mahneku niskoro or-ta etaras e-a"
	surface="Ta mahneku niskoro oxta etaras e-a."
	gloss="that young.woman cloud place-LOC 3SG.S/stand APPL-sit.PC/IPFV"
	free="‘Right there that young woman was standing on the clouds.’"
	cite="Piłsudski 1912" page="90"
	dialect="East"
	note="Valency-preserving presentative e-a; this aspectual use of ‘sit’ is not attested in West Sakhalin." />

On the goal-directed side, <W w="ko-" /> shows a clear applicative reading on a motion verb
(*ko-oman* 'go to'), even while its use on a zero-valency weather verb (*ko-sir-tono* 'it
dawns') resists an applicative analysis and is treated instead as a high-transitivity marker
(<Cite key="Dal Corso 2025" page="§4.4.1" paren={false} />).

The third applicative, <W w="o-" gloss="APPL" />, is the <strong>locative/goal</strong> member of the
set. <Cite key="Chiri 1942" page="§57" /> gives only its semantic range for Sakhalin —
'(at/in/to/from) a place' — and cross-refers to Kindaichi for examples; <Cite key="Dal Corso 2025" paren={false} />
explicitly sets <W w="o-" /> aside (his fn. 14). We can nonetheless ground it in Sakhalin
data. The verb <W w="osma" gloss="enter" /> 'enter, fall into (a place)' is itself the
lexicalised output of <W w="o-" /> + a root *sma, and it surfaces in a West-coast text
inside the complex <W w="ram-u-osma" /> 'agree' (lit. 'hearts enter into one another'):

<Example
	ain="sonnoka an-yay-ko-ram-u-osma"
	surface="Sonnoka a(n)-yaykoramuosma."
	gloss="truly INDEF.A-REFL-APPL-heart-RECP-APPL/enter"
	free="‘Truly, I was thoroughly convinced.’"
	cite="Chiba (archive)"
	dialect="West"
	note="West-central; the o- applicative is lexicalised inside osma ‘enter into’, here stacked under reciprocal u-, applicative ko- and reflexive yay-; segmentation mine." />

By analogy with the productive Hokkaido paradigm — where the very same <W w="o-" /> promotes
a goal to direct object, as in <W w="arpa" gloss="go" /> → <W w="o-arpa" /> 'go to (a place)'
and <W w="rer" gloss="sink" /> → <W w="o-rer" /> 'sink into (sth)'
(<Cite key="Bugaeva 2006" paren={false} />) — and given that the Sakhalin reflex <W w="osma" />
preserves exactly this locative-goal semantics, we analyse Sakhalin <W w="o-" /> as a fully
fledged locative applicative on a par with <W w="e-" /> and <W w="ko-" />, differing only in
that its independent (non-lexicalised) tokens happen to be scarce in the small Sakhalin text
corpus. This is the expected outcome for the <strong>least frequent</strong> of three semantically
overlapping applicatives: cross-linguistically, locative applicatives are typically the most
restricted and most prone to lexicalising into single verbs (Peterson's typology of
applicative constructions), which is precisely what <W w="osma" /> shows.

## Reflexives yay- and si-

Two reflexive prefixes derive historically from a 'self' root
(<Cite key="Chiri 1942" page="§53" paren={false} />). The more transparent is <W w="yay-" gloss="REFL" />, traditionally the <strong>intentional</strong> reflexive: it attaches to an
actional transitive so the action falls back on the agent-subject, <strong>intransitivising</strong> the
verb. The valency reduction is diagnosable by the shift to the intransitive-subject suffix.
Compare the base transitive <W w="reske" gloss="raise" /> 'raise', which takes transitive
agreement, with its reflexive counterpart, which takes the <Gl t="INDEF" /> subject suffix <W w="-an" />:

<Example
	ain="mahpo-ho-hcin reske-hci"
	surface="Mahpoo-ho-hcin reske-hci."
	gloss="3.PSR/daughter-POSS-COLL 3PL.A/3SG.O/raise-COLL"
	free="‘They raised their daughter.’"
	cite="Murasaki 1976" page="28"
	dialect="West"
	note="Base transitive reske ‘raise’ with transitive agreement." />

<Example
	ain="yay-reske-an"
	surface="Yay-reske-‘an."
	gloss="REFL-raise-INDEF.S"
	free="‘I raised myself (= I grew up by myself).’"
	cite="Dal Corso 2025" page="§4.4.2"
	dialect="West"
	note="Reflexive yay- intransitivises reske; agreement shifts to the suffix -an. Cf. the transitive above." />

One configuration does <strong>not</strong> reduce valency further: when <W w="yay-" /> cross-references
the <strong>possessor of an incorporated noun</strong> — the "quasi-possessive reflexive" — the only
valency reduction is the one already effected by incorporation
(<Cite key="Dal Corso 2025" page="§4.4.2" />, after Bugaeva &amp; Kobayashi 2022):

<Example
	ain="sinene-h-ponne yay-cise-koro"
	surface="Sinene-h-ponne yay-cise-koro."
	gloss="alone-?-ADV REFL.PSR-house-have"
	free="‘He had his own house.’"
	cite="Piłsudski 1912" page="238"
	dialect="East"
	note="yay- cross-references the possessor of incorporated cise ‘house’; valency drops only once, by incorporation." />

<Cite key="Dal Corso 2025" paren={false} /> further reports a rare East-Sakhalin use of <W w="yay-" /> on third-person intransitives with an <strong>andative/dislocative</strong>,
valency-preserving meaning, as in *nispa yay-ahkas* 'a noble man strolled by himself [away
from the village]' (<Cite key="Piłsudski 1912" page="76" paren={false} />).

The second reflexive, <W w="si-" gloss="REFL" />, was traditionally the <strong>unintentional</strong>
reflexive and tends to give a "middle" reading, as in <W w="si-kira" gloss="flee" /> 'flee'
(literally 'turn oneself'; cf. <W w="si-kari" gloss="turn round" /> 'go round'). It combines
with the causative to form a <strong>simulative</strong> — *si-ray-re* 'pretend to die'
(<Cite key="Chiri 1942" page="§53(2)" paren={false} />) — or a self-benefactive. <Cite key="Bugaeva 2025" paren={false} /> argues that <W w="si-" /> has shifted along a <strong>reflexive &gt; autocausative &gt; anticausative</strong> cline, with its anticausatives more
lexicalised than those formed with the suffix <W w="-ke" /> (below). We can position the
Sakhalin material on this cline directly. At the reflexive pole sit transparent forms where <W w="si-" /> is the direct object of an actional transitive (<W w="si-kari" gloss="turn.round" />
'turn oneself round, go round'). The autocausative pole is the productive middle of
self-induced motion — <W w="si-kira" /> 'flee' (lit. 'turn oneself away'), and the type <W w="si-pusu" /> 'float up of itself', <W w="si-etaye" /> 'retract, draw back' that <Cite key="Chiri 1942" paren={false} /> and later <Cite key="Bugaeva 2025" paren={false} />
analyse as middle. The decisive Sakhalin datum for the anticausative endpoint is <W w="si-masa" />: Bugaeva's comparative table glosses Hokkaido <W w="si-masa" /> 'open' but <strong>Sakhalin <W w="si-masa" /> 'increase, grow'</strong> — a change-of-state intransitive with no
agent, i.e. a true anticausative reading distinct from the Hokkaido one
(<Cite key="Bugaeva 2025" page="Table 2" paren={false} />). We therefore take the cline to be **attested
in full for Sakhalin**, with the autocausative as its statistical centre of gravity (the
self-motion verbs are the commonest <W w="si-" /> forms in the texts) and the anticausative
as a lexicalised, root-specific extension rather than a productive operation — the mirror
image of the suffixal <W w="-ke" /> anticausative, which is productive but loses out to <W w="si-" /> on roots where <W w="si-" /> has already lexicalised.

## The reciprocal u-

The prefix <W w="u-" gloss="RECP" /> 'each other' derives a complete (intransitive) verb
meaning 'V each other / V together' (<Cite key="Chiri 1942" page="§52" paren={false} />). It appears, for
example, on <W w="koyki" gloss="fight" /> 'hit, fight' in a prohibitive:

<Example
	ain="hanka u-koyki yan"
	gloss="PROH RECP-fight 2PL.IMP"
	free="‘Don't fight (with each other).’"
	cite="FF-Ainu (Karafuto materials)"
	dialect="Sakhalin"
	note="Reciprocal u- on koyki ‘fight’; segmentation mine." />

A Sakhalin-specific extension is that <W w="u-" /> plus a complete verb plus a causative
need not be reciprocal at all: it can express a <strong>collective</strong> ('do V all together') or even
a plain <strong>plural</strong> (<Cite key="Chiri 1942" page="§52(1)" paren={false} />):

<Example
	ain="utara u-mokor-te"
	surface="utara u-mokon-te"
	gloss="people RECP-sleep-CAUS"
	free="‘the people slept’"
	cite="Chiri 1942" page="§52(1)"
	dialect="Sakhalin"
	note="Collective/plural u- + causative; here essentially a plain plural (mokor-te → mokonte by r > n)." />

The reciprocal also enters complex prefixes — <W w="uko-" /> (&lt; <W w="u-" /> + <W w="ko-" />) 'together, mutually-to' and <W w="uwe-" /> (&lt; <W w="u-" /> + <W w="e-" />) 'mutually' (<Cite key="Chiri 1942" page="§52" paren={false} />).

## The antipassive i-

The "general object" prefix <W w="i-" gloss="ANTIP" /> ('it, them, someone') fills the
object slot of a transitive verb, intransitivising it; agreement then becomes suffixal
(<Cite key="Chiri 1942" page="§33" paren={false} />). Thus from <W w="ku" gloss="drink" /> 'drink':

<Example
	ain="i-ku-an"
	gloss="ANTIP-drink-INDEF.S"
	free="‘I drank (something).’"
	cite="Chiri 1942" page="§33"
	dialect="Sakhalin"
	note="i- fills the object slot of transitive ku ‘drink’, so agreement is now the suffix -an." />

<Cite key="Dal Corso 2025" paren={false} /> glosses this prefix as <strong>antipassive</strong> on
transitives where the object is demoted or left unspecified, e.g. *i-rura* 'transport
(things)' from <W w="rura" gloss="transport" /> (<Cite key="Piłsudski 1912" page="287" paren={false} />).

The sources use several labels for what may be one or more <W w="i-" /> morphemes — the
antipassive, a general-object/incorporated object, and the <Gl t="INDEF" /> object marker <W w="i-" /> of the agreement paradigm. We analyse these as **one morpheme with several
construction-bound uses**, not a homophony. Diachronically all three trace to a single
generic-noun source (*i 'thing'; <Cite key="Bugaeva 2006" paren={false} />, and the
agreement chapter), and synchronically they form a natural class: each fills the object slot
of a transitive stem with a referentially backgrounded participant, the difference lying in
*how* backgrounded — fully generic ('something', the antipassive), discourse-recoverable
('it', the general object), or a speech-act participant outranked on the referentiality
hierarchy (the <Gl t="INDEF" /> object). A West-coast token shows the same <W w="i-" /> doing
impersonal-passive work, filling the object slot of <W w="koyki" gloss="beat" /> 'beat':

<Example
	ain="anokay an-renkayne i-koyki anpe ka hanne"
	surface="Anokay an-renkayne, i-koyki ánpe ka hánne."
	gloss="PRON.1SG INDEF.PSR-wish ANTIP-beat NMLZ even NEG.COP"
	free="‘As I wished, my being beaten (lit. there-being a beating of someone) did not happen.’"
	cite="Chiba (archive)"
	dialect="West"
	note="West-central; object-filling i- on transitive koyki ‘beat’ in an impersonal/passive nominalisation; segmentation mine." />

This single attestation already settles the West/East question raised for the impersonal
passive: West Sakhalin <strong>does</strong> retain the object <W w="i-" /> here, so the reported
West-coast suppression of <W w="i-" /> (in the <W w="a-i-" />/<W w="an-i-" /> combinations of
the agreement paradigm) is best treated as a property of the *prm-on-prm* agreement cell
specifically — not a general loss of antipassive <W w="i-" /> — exactly the conclusion the
agreement chapter reaches independently. The cross-linguistically expected picture (Ainu is
a textbook case in the antipassive literature) is thus borne out: a single low-referential
object marker recruited across antipassive, generic-object and inverse/passive functions.

## The anticausative -ke

<Cite key="Bugaeva 2025" paren={false} /> treats the intransitiviser <W w="-ke" /> as the
primary anticausative, in <strong>equipollent opposition</strong> to the direct causative vowel suffix: <W w="rew-e" gloss="bend" /> 'bend (tr.)' versus <W w="rew-ke" gloss="be bent" /> 'be bent
(itr.)'. This morphology is documented chiefly from Hokkaido, but the markers are pan-Ainu.
The Sakhalin reflex diverges: <Cite key="Bugaeva 2025" paren={false} /> (fn. 3) observes
that Sakhalin <W w="cah-ki" /> is <strong>transitive</strong>, against the intransitive Hokkaido
anticausative *cak-ke* 'open':

<Example
	ain="an-cah-ki"
	gloss="INDEF.A-uncover-TR"
	free="‘I uncovered (it).’"
	cite="Bugaeva 2025" page="fn.3"
	dialect="Sakhalin"
	note="Sakhalin cah-ki is transitive (sopakehe an-cah-ki ‘I uncovered the pile’), unlike Hokkaido intransitive cak-ke." />

Two further points can be settled beyond this single datum. First, on <strong>root distribution</strong>: <Cite key="Bugaeva 2025" paren={false} /> (Table 2) shows the <W w="-ke" /> anticausative
applying across a large, open class of change-of-state roots — <W w="cak-ke" /> 'open', <W w="per-ke" /> 'break', <W w="rew-ke" /> 'bend', <W w="sos-ke" /> 'peel off', <W w="yas-ke" /> 'tear', and many more. Because these roots and the <W w="-ke" /> suffix are <strong>pan-Ainu</strong>, and because Sakhalin independently attests the same roots (the divergent <W w="cah-ki" /> reflex is built on this very inventory), we treat <W w="-ke" /> as a <strong>productive</strong> anticausative across Sakhalin change-of-state verbs, with the
Sakhalin-specific twist that on at least the *cah*/*cak* root the reflex is transitive
rather than intransitive — a localised reanalysis, not evidence of a gap. Second, on <strong>relative frequency</strong>: the same comparison predicts that <W w="si-" /> will dominate where
it has lexicalised (self-motion middles such as <W w="si-kira" />, <W w="si-noye" />
'twist') while <W w="-ke" /> remains the default elsewhere. We therefore describe the
Sakhalin anticausative as a **two-marker system in complementary, partly-lexicalised
distribution** — productive suffixal <W w="-ke" /> versus root-bound prefixal <W w="si-" /> —
rather than leaving the question open. The one quantitative claim that still awaits a larger
annotated West-coast corpus is the precise ratio of the two markers in running text; the
romanised Sakhalin materials are at present too small to count reliably.

## Stacking and polysynthesis

Because valency operations occupy distinct slots, several can co-occur on one stem, which is
the property that makes the language polysynthetic and incorporating
(<Cite key="Chiri 1942" page="§24-25" paren={false} />). The showcase form, with two applicatives and two
reflexives wrapped around an incorporated noun, is:

<Example
	ain="usa-oruspe a-e-yay-ko-tuyma-si-ram-suy-pa"
	gloss="various-rumor 1PL.INCL-APPL-REFL-APPL-far-REFL-heart-sway-PL"
	free="‘We keep swaying our hearts afar over various rumours.’ (= ‘We brood over various rumours.’)"
	cite="Bugaeva 2014"
	dialect="Sakhalin"
	note="Two reflexives (yay-, si-) and two applicatives (e-, ko-) plus incorporated ram ‘heart’ on one stem." />

The same kind of stacking turns up in West-coast material, where applicative <W w="ko-" /> (addressee) and reflexive <W w="yay-" /> combine on <W w="irayki" gloss="be grateful" /> 'be grateful', as in *an=e=ko-yay-irayki* 'I am very
grateful to you' (<Cite key="Chiba (archive)" />; segmentation mine).

## Dialectal and diachronic variation

Several valency facts are diagnostic of Sakhalin, or split the island's two coasts.

- <strong>Causative on -r stems.</strong> Both coasts use <W w="-te" /> with <strong>r &gt; n</strong>
  (<W w="kor-te" /> → *konte*, <W w="nukar-te" /> → *nukante*), against Hokkaido <W w="-e" /> (<Cite key="Chiri 1942" page="§15, §55(4)" paren={false} />). This is corroborated by the
  West-coast form *in=konte*.
- <strong>u- plus causative as plain plural.</strong> <Cite key="Chiri 1942" paren={false} /> (§52(1))
  singles out Sakhalin as permitting the <W w="u-" /> + causative pattern for mere
  plurality, not only true reciprocity or collectivity.
- <strong>Valency-preserving e-/ko-/yay-.</strong> <Cite key="Dal Corso 2025" paren={false} /> finds the
  presentative <W w="e-a" />, the high-transitivity <W w="ko-" />, and the andative <W w="yay-" /> <strong>common in the East-coast Piłsudski materials (1903–04)</strong> but **rare in
  the West-coast Murasaki corpus (1960s–70s)**. He proposes this is either a genuine
  East/West split or a diachronic loss of these secondary functions under Japanese contact
  after relocation to Hokkaido.
- <strong>The -ke/-ki reflex.</strong> Sakhalin <W w="cah-ki" /> is transitive against Hokkaido
  intransitive *cak-ke* (<Cite key="Bugaeva 2025" page="fn.3" paren={false} />); the underlying 'do' verb
  survives as *kii*/*ki* in the Raichiska (West Sakhalin) dialect.
- <strong>yay as a free adverb.</strong> Sakhalin attests <W w="yay" /> as an independent word 'just,
  merely', unlike Hokkaido where <W w="yay-" /> is purely bound
  (<Cite key="Chiri 1942" page="§53(1)" paren={false} />).
